reviews.review_text:
a mono FM broadcast? Hi GD fans, 

Yep,  not a bad 1990 late spring show.  It always comes down to the source and anyone that has listened to a lot of live bootleg or fan based recordings knows they can be unforgiving; sometimes with new technology it can't be improved.  Alas,  this is the case for this source; a great effort by our crack team of enthusiasts but this FM broadcast is in mono.  I kid you not,  on my main rig in my studio I use a Mackie Big Knob for a general input monitoring.  It has a "mono" button, when I press it, there is no stereo to collapse, so the source is mono.  That's not a bad thing but for a 1990 FM broadcast is highly unusual.  What are ya gonna do ...?  

The show it self is average but with a great setlist in my opinion.  It's not a bad listen but sounds rather Lo Fi ... might be a campfire boombox listen if you know what I mean... maybe some body can grab a different soundboard source ?

Amazing Set at a rare venue This dude mentioning mono has a point the recording does seem to be polarized to one side. It's hard to hear Bobby and Phil but the clarity is crystal. The energy is amazing. --- > upon second comparison to the tapers recordings, they are identical to this one it was the mix of the show. For some reason Bob and Phil are barely audible while Jerry and Brent have high volume. It was a blunder by the sound man probably got a little spaced out!
